frequent_values: This year was another exciting year of art for students at PS 15, as we continue to expand our programs and partners (adding Puppetry this year). In addition, through implementation of the School-wide Enrichment Model, the faculty and staff have played an integral part in providing sustainable arts programming based on student-interest in clusters such as “Art for Change,” “Photography,” “Making Music” and “Trash to Treasure”. We continued residency programs with organizations such as The Children's Museum of Art, Mark DeGarmo Dance and Third Street Music, in which kindergarten through fifth grade students learned through the Orff Shulwerk approach. Students explored basic rhythms/melodies using various instruments. All our students visited arts museums, films and performances to supplement and extend arts learning objectives grown out of classroom curriculum. We continued our nine-year relationship with Arts for All, Inc, providing our kindergarten through second grade students with opportunities to integrate theater and visual art into literacy. Our students have many opportunities to express themselves through dance, music, and theater with our partnerships with Mark DeGarmo Dance, Rosie’s Broadway Kids, puppetry with Arts Connection and creative storytelling with Story Pirates. Lastly, through our Technology Arts class, students study mentor artists, learn coding, graphic design, and animation. We expect to have many submissions to this year’s District 1 Arts Fair and close the year on a high note for Arts at PS 15!

We strongly believe that the arts should be an important part of a school's academic program. We have participated in and developed a wide variety of educational programs and activities to support the inclusion of the arts (music, art, movement and drama) in the daily curriculum offerings to our students. Many community agencies support us including Third Street Music School, Rosie's Broadway Kids and the Beacon after school program. Visitors to PS 19 often comment on the extent to which the students are engaged with their work. We are particularly proud of our school's warm and sociable tone and productive learning environment.

Every student at PS 20 is engaged in the arts in a variety of ways. Our current partnerships have allowed us to provide dance and movement instruction to all of our students in grades 2-5. Turtle Bay Music School continues to provide ORFF and world music classes to our students in grades PK-2 as well as a chorus for our 3rd graders. Our classroom teachers, cluster teachers, and our partners work closely to integrate the arts into our units of study. In addition to our many partnerships, we have a school based visual arts teacher and music teacher who meet with most of the classes once a week. Both arts teachers try to coordinate their curriculum with the literacy and social studies curriculum. Another partnership we are very proud of is our that with American BaLLET Theater, our 5th graders get too learn ballet and theater. The students get an opportunity to perform at the Metropolitan Opera House at the end of the year. Our Fourth graders dance all year with teachers from the National Dance Institute and have 2 performances for Families and school. In addition, our 5th graders get to be part of Rosie's Broadway Kids, this program gives them the opportunity to go to a Broadway show. They also have weekly dance classes for half of the school year. Our Art teacher and Music teacher are active all year teaching all our students to play instruments and different fine arts techniques. This year they will have a Arts festival day where they will present to the student.We are always looking for new ways to expand our programming

Our school currently offers music instruction by a certified full-time music teacher. The CCLS aligned curriculum taught is primarily string instruments. Students perform in a winter and spring concert. Our school partners with two community based organizations that provide visual arts and music instruction. We continue to partner with Rosie's Kids theater program.

longest_values: The Arts Program at PS/IS 206 includes two certified visual arts teachers, two certified music teachers, one certified drama teacher and one certified dance teacher. In the 2017-18 school year, PS/IS 206 will be adding an additional visual arts teacher to the Arts department. The elementary music program at P.S. 206 is a sequenced program that addresses musical feeling, concepts, music literacy, cultural context, and performance. The middle school program includes General Music building a foundation of music which includes:  the instruments of the orchestra, traditional notation, tablature, Western and World Music History, musical theater and the Little Kids Rock Modern Band Program. Performances are done throughout the school year. The Dance program at P.S./I.S. 206 is a creative based program focused on the Elements of Dance and techniques such as Ballet, Modern, Jazz, Hip-Hop, and cultural dance forms. Through the Blueprint for the Arts in Dance, we study various choreographers, and the history of each dance form. Students are creative choreographers through the art of dance-making including a partnership with Alvin Ailey. The PS 206 theatre program is designed to introduce students to theatre as an art for and means of communication, engage their creativity in developing original performance material, and build their skills as theatre artists and lifelong learners. The Visual Arts Program at is aligned with the NYC Blueprint for Arts and students explore drawing, painting, sculpture paper-mache, printmaking, and collage.

Queens School of Inquiry is a 6-12 Early College Initiative School. All middle school students receive instruction in art,music, and theater. Students learn the basics in drawing, painting, art history and art criticism in 6th and 7th grade. In music, all students gain basic knowledge in reading and composing music and all students learn to play the recorder and violin/viola in 6th and 7th grade. In theater, all 8th grade students take the Introduction to Musical Theatre course. When students enter high school, every freshman student is scheduled for Acting I & II. Opportunities are extended to students who wish to enroll in advanced level drama courses, college art courses and/or high school art/music electives. Outside of the school day, QSI offers MS Musical, art club and SING!. The mission of the Queen's School of Inquiry Arts Department is to foster a passion and dedication for the Visual, Musical, and Theatrical Arts. We want our students to become collaborative creators of culture and change through the various artistic disciplines while exploring their identity. Beginning in 6th grade and continuing until 12th grade, students are exposed to many aspects of the arts including: acting, analysis, criticism, dance, design, directing, music, playwriting, history, research, and visual arts. The QSI Arts Department is expanding in the 2017-2018 school year. Our current 10th grade students will have the ability to receive an advanced arts diploma designated in theater if they fulfill 10 credits in theater related coursework.

Every year, PS 86 strives to improve our arts programming. Our music teacher is a certified music professional who is trained and knowledgeable in instrumental, chorus, and overall in creating musical scores with the students. Our lessons are interdisciplinary and with our ongoing curriculum writing, this enables us to improve our shows and assemblies, while supporting the arts. We currently have two Art teachers who service the students with visual arts in the classroom. The Theatre Arts teacher encompasses the arts, theatre, and literacy.The students are not the only ones learning and growing. Our parent involvement has increased with each passing year through the arts and craft sessions provided by the school. We encourage parents to participate in arts/crafts, tutorials, museum trips, and live day and evening performances. Our annual Art Day is the culminating event preceded by a month long study of a famous artist. Our multicultural fashion show in February, depicts the fashion, art, dance moves, and music of a particular country from around the world. Our music teacher has immersed our students with learning the piano and the guitar for 4th and 5th grades. Our poetry club performs in a poetry performance which includes and culminates in a student-based, student created, movie, filmed and edited by our PE teacher. Our 5th grade chorus performs at The National Choral Festival each year for the past four years. Overall, the students have the opportunity to become inspired while becoming lifelong learners through the arts.

Students at the Louis Armstrong Middle School are given a number of opportunities to participate in the music and art departments. In the 5th grade, all students learn the recorder;sing folk songs from around the world, often celebrating the student’s ancestral heritage, and apply movement to their music making. 6th graders have a number of options that prepare them for continued study in 7th and 8th grade. In general music, students continue using the mallet percussion and drums while learning basic music theory and solfege.In the ensembles: chorus, band and orchestra, students learn how to read music and learn to apply musical notation to a number of genres from the Baroque era to popular music throughout the years. It is the mission of the music department to teach students to be life-long learners. Much emphasis includes working towards preparing students for performing arts high schools to become career and ready in any subject area. In our Art classes, we enable students to use a variety of processes to stimulate creative products, manipulatives, and self-determined learning and making. Students explore all different means of mediums while putting together portfolios for specialized high schools. Art classes are actively engaged in using self and peer assessment to promote growth and revision within their projects. Art students adhere to the blueprints while exploring contemporary movements in the Art world today. Self-contained classes enjoy differentiated Art experiences. All students celebrate yearly in the Art show

In visual arts students are exposed to a curriculum-based program that helps them understand how material, technique and process are used to create works of art. Students understand how art has a variety of functions within historical and cultural contexts. Resources at the school, like iPads with museum Apps, help students become familiar with all kinds of art forms and hone their ability to observe and discuss their own artworks and the works of art of others. The program is enhanced with museum visits and a year-round calendar of exhibitions showcasing students' work. In theater, pre-k and kindergarten students activate and use their imagination through creative drama activities with storytelling components. First graders explore ensemble acting and memorization techniques through participatory stories that include folktales from different cultures. Second graders develop the actor’s instruments: voice, body and mind, while participating in play productions. Third and fourth graders engage in complex acting settings such as full-length rehearsals or scene work to explore theater making processes through various roles: the actor, the director, the designer, the spectator and the critic. Dual language students in fourth grade are trained in Jacques Lecoq’s Pantomime for Actors Technique which prepare them for the experimental theater course in fifth grade. Other fifth grade classes focus on acting or playwriting, and a specific theme or historic period such as Elizabethan Theater, Ancient Greek Theater and Musical Theater.

frequent_values: We did not receive 21st Century Grant, as we had for the past 14 years, that supported the arts program at M140.  Budget does not allow for M140 to sustain many, and possibly all partnerships with Arts organizations.

Our school enrollment is approximately 97% Title 1 eligible, with disproportionately high representation of student groups most at risk:  47% of our students live in temporary housing (2nd highest percent across NYC public schools); 33% are classified as Students with Disabilities; 28% are English Language Learners; 66% are Latino and 32% are African American.  The arts play a vital role in engaging our students both during the regular school day and in extended day programming, and contribute dramatically to our vibrant school culture.
A register loss has had a significant impact on our budget and has limited our ability to provide a vast array of art experiences.
2017-2018 School year will be the first school year we are building sequential arts programming. We will be offering arts tracks in dance, music, and visual arts to interested and talented students.

longest_values: The Visual art program at P.S. 138 helps students develop confidence, creativity and literacy througgh creative projects.The curriculum is align with the standards and benchmarks set forth by NYC DOE blueprint for Visual Art.PS 138, art program goal is to make art the starting point with art making.By connecting art to every subject in the school's curriculum, and by interconnecting a multidisciplinary art program, students not only benefit from the structure of each class, but also from their diversity.The art program is intergrating between every subject in other to give student a rich ,well varied, and all-emcompas art education. Throught the expolration of a variety media- drawings, collage, painting, and now theater, Ps 138 is helping students develop an understanding of the principal of art and the elements of design. Students are able to use academic art language to discuss artworks and always cite "visual evidence" to support inferences, claim, and arguments made about a work of art. Goal 1: To increase student's awareness of Visual arts. 1)Introcuce different artist, art element, principles of design, and art forms to students.Goal 2: To demonstrade and develop Arts methods that support students achievement. Goal 3:To educate students about art, as well as celebrate students's creativity.This year,PS 138 partner with The New Victory theater to enhance art instruction in the middle school. Our Visual art program strives to give all students a well rounded art experience, and encourage them to create a work of art.

Our school is committed to providing our students with a rich and diverse arts experience. This experience includes exposure to all arts disciplines, integration of art into the instructional program and exposure to all of our city's art rich cultural institutions and resources. Our students learn to appreciate art in their environment and they understand how art contributes to their lives. Our teachers are also committed to art learning through ongoing professional development offered throughout the year. They integrate visual arts into all subject areas and help students explore their creative talents in a variety of disciplines including visual arts, drama, music, dance and technology. We have great arts partnerships that help us to provide students with rich experience in all of the above. We provide music exposure and learning to all of our early childhood students and we offer instrumental music instruction in woodwinds, percussion and violin to students in third through eighth grade. Our goal moving forward is to grow our art program so that there is cumulative learning in visual arts and music in pre-kindergarten through eighth grade and to integrate theater arts into the middle school curriculum so that there is alignment to content area learning. We also seek additional funds for instruction in  visual arts on every grade.  "Excellence, Engagement and Enrichment" is our mission statement and we are committed to offering our students a well rounded arts experience utilizing our school and city resources.

The Arts program at Philippa Schyuler Middle School for the Gifted & Talented has been one of our prized jewels for many years! This versatile program offers students the opportunity to study a variety of disciplines. From Modern and Urban dance to Steel Pan and Concert Band, our students are immersed in learning activities that afford them the chance to express themselves and showcase their many talents in a multitude of ways. This year, one of our school's goals has been to continue to enrich and expand the Performing & Visual Arts program within our school community. Given this focus, we have boosted our level of performance, and expanded both of our annual winter and spring concerts to encompass more diversity and theatrical elements. We also put together an elaborate production of the theatrical play, Antigone, with full cast and crew! We have also expanded on our International Day celebrations to include more performance opportunities that highlight a variety of cultures. In addition, we have created partnerships with local Arts Educational programs to prepare our students with the foundational skills needed to succeed in these realms. Through these comprehensive programs, students learn valuable, life-long skills that are necessary to working in large and diverse groups. Additionally, they broaden the scope of our school community, allowing for teachers, students and parents to come together and acknowledge the hard work and diligence found within our Performing and Visual Arts Program.
